le, Lynch offers an intimate portrait of the people who work there, a nuanced explanation of the company's hiring practices, and a cogent analysis of how the workers' experiences can inform our understanding of aging and work in the twenty-first century. As an in-depth study of a singular workplace, rooted in the unique insights of an anthropologist who specializes in the world of work, this book provides a sustained focus on values and meanings—with profound consequences for the broader assumptions our society has about aging and employment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aManufacturing industriesxEmployeesxMassachusettsxNeedham. 0aManufacturing industrieszMassachusettszNeedhamxEmployees. 0aOlder peoplexEmploymentxMassachusettsxNeedham. 0aOlder peoplexEmploymentzMassachusettszNeedham. 0aRetirementxMassachusettsxNeedham. 0aRetirementzMassachusettszNeedham. 4aAnthropology. 4aLabor History.  aretirement age, aging, old workers, vita needle company, elderly workforce, hiring practices, ageism.1 aDowney, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146409640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801464096423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801464096/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles